column1: 0,pDIsEZsalAo,2018-05-23T15:33:40Z,UCIcCXe3iWo6lq-iWKV40Oug,FL Studio 20  -  Complete Beginner Basics Tutorial,"This video is the first in the FL Studio 20 Basics Playlist and is to help those who are completely new to FL Studio and are looking for a place to start. When loading a synth for the first time, I would recommend using ""FLEX"" it is the best and most easy to use and was added after I made this video.
Watch the FL Studio 20 Basics Playlist here : https://goo.gl/2Yxrf2
I try to simplify the DAW and it's signal flow for those who are not familiar with FL Studio's workflow.
This video shows how to navigate the Browser, Channel Rack, Playlist, Piano Roll and Mixer so that you can start making music :)
There are far too many features to cover in one video but luckily there are lots more (shorter) videos on each topic.
For more detailed videos on each topic -

Note - Your FL Studio version might look a little different depending on your screen size and resolution. I also have the effects on the mixer default to the left hand side- yours might be on the right, this doesn't change the function :)

column1: Start Producing Your Own Music in FL Studio 20

This tutorial is the first few sections taken from our Complete FL Studio Course. This course is all about FL Studio, which is software for music sequencing and is a digital audio workstation for Windows and OS X.
FL Studio is used across professional studios and bedroom studios worldwide. Learning how to use your DAW correctly will dramatically improve the quality of your music and the speed you create it.
NOTE: This tutorial is for all versions of FL Studio. Some of the features I discuss in this Complete Course will only be available for FL Studio 20 Producer and above.
What is this FL Studio 20 Beginners Tutorial all about?
In this beginners guide to FL Studio, you will gain a basic overview of some of the main functions and features in FL Studio.

How to Make a Sub Bass in FL Studio (3xOsc Sub Bass & Sytrus Sub Bass)

column1: In this video, you will get essential tips how to make a sub bass in FL Studio with 3x Osc & Sytrus. A sub bass is the lowest effective frequency of a sound, usually between 60 and 30 Hz, that you will find in kicks and/or basses.
Make sure to watch until the end, as you will discover an ultimate strategy to make unlimited harmonic-rich basses...
If you want to learn more about the essential basics of synthesis, start now with the Sound Design for Beginners guide by clicking this link: https://amazon.com/dp/B07MCQLNLJ

How to Make a Sub Bass in FL Studio (3xOsc Sub Bass & Sytrus Sub Bass)

In this video, you will get essential tips how to make a sub bass in FL Studio with 3x Osc & Sytrus. A sub bass is the lowest effective frequency of a sound, usually between 60 and 30 Hz, that you will find in kicks and/or basses.

Make sure to watch until the end, as you will discover an ultimate strategy to make unlimited harmonic-rich basses...

column1: 100,wfwT2AtIlt8,2019-04-06T16:30:17Z,UCIcCXe3iWo6lq-iWKV40Oug,The Most Underrated Plugin In FL Studio - Fruity Convolver Tutorial,"In this video I show you one of the most underrated plugins in FL Studio - The Fruity Convolver.
It is used to simulate, with high precision, natural acoustic spaces and Hardware reverb units.

It does this using convolution mathematics and an impulse response of the room/hardware. Luckily for us, we don't need to know anything complicated to get fantastic results that are not possibly with an algorithmic reverb like Fruity Reverb 2.

120,TJoZEsZtrc0,2021-09-18T16:30:03Z,UCIcCXe3iWo6lq-iWKV40Oug,Stereo Shaper Tutorial - Everything You Need To Know,"Learn how to use the Fruity Stereo Shaper for mid-side, left-right and stereo processing.

The Fruity Stereo Shaper in FL Studio is an excellent tool for splitting and isolating audio signals. It can be used for Mid-Side, Left-Right processing and a whole range of other polarity and phase related tasks.

In the first example, the Stereo Shaper is used to separate the Mid and Side channels. Mid is anything which is the same in both left and right channels - not just mono. The Side is anything which is not the same in the left and right channels. When separated, we can edit each channel independently and create a wider and deeper sound.

In the second example we split up the signal into the left and right channels. This is not the same as panning the whole audio signal to the left or right. It actually mutes everything on one side. This is excellent if you are working with stereo recordings and want to ""undo"" the previous panning. You can separate hard panned signals and apply fresh processing to each side which will again create more width.

0:00 - Intro
0:25 - How to Load Stereo Shaper
1:45 - Mid Side Processing
4:38 - Left Right Processing
6:05 - All Controls Explained

The Fruity Stereo Shaper in FL Studio is an excellent tool for splitting and isolating audio signals. It can be used for Mid-Side, Left-Right processing and a whole range of other polarity and phase related tasks. 

Mid Side:

 In the first example, the Stereo Shaper is used to separate the Mid and Side channels. Mid is anything which is the same in both left and right channels - not just mono. The Side is anything which is not the same in the left and right channels. When separated, we can edit each channel independently and create a wider and deeper sound.


Left Right:

In the second example we split up the signal into the left and right channels. This is not the same as panning the whole audio signal to the left or right. It actually mutes everything on one side. This is excellent if you are working with stereo recordings and want to ""undo"" the previous panning. You can separate hard panned signals and apply fresh processing to each side which will again create more width. 

Videos for further study:

Phase and Polarity Explained: https://youtu.be/IrXHVWPGdeQ
Left-Right EQ Trick: https://youtu.be/RzRmw4rNY90

Launchpad S is fully USB bus powered -- no need for power sockets or batteries -- and it's lightweight and easy to carry anywhere.

Launch Control is a robust, compact controller with 16 assignable knobs and eight pads - ideal for hands-on control of your mixer, instruments and effects. Including volume, pans, sends, track arming, soloing and muting. Launchpad S lets you jump to different levels across eight channels at once
 
‚Ä¢Launchpad iPad app
Trigger loops and effects using the Launchpad app on iPad -- Launchpad S can be plugged into your iPad and fully powered with a Camera Connection Kit
 
‚Ä¢Take it anywhere
Launchpad S is fully USB bus powered -- no need for power sockets or batteries -- and it's lightweight and easy to carry anywhere.
 
‚Ä¢More software and sample content
Comes with the Novation Bass Station synth plug-in and over one gigabyte of Loopmasters samples

Launch Control is a robust, compact controller with 16 assignable knobs and eight pads - ideal for hands-on control of your mixer, instruments and effects. Designed to partner with Novation Launchpad, Launch Control works with all major music software -- and with your iPad. Use Launch Control's pads to fire off samples while you use the knobs to tweak filters, levels, and effects controls.

For more videos subscribe to our YouTube channel here:
http://www.youtube.com/novationtv""}",,

It is an incredible tool for music production and in this video I give you a complete beginner to advanced guide of the plugin and showcase a few of it's sounds.

It's designed to be a professional, preset based synth with the ability to control macros and parameters to fine tune each preset to your needs. They have focused on making the presets as usable as possible - they are not simply trying to fill up space. There are packs from some incredible sound designers and many more to come in the future.
I like the user interface and I think the whole image line team should be very proud of this big step forward for FL Studio 20. It's one of the best stock plugins I've seen in a long time.
Many are calling this the FL Studio version of Nexus but I believe it will be so much more - and the GUI is far better than reFX Nexus.
Log into your image line account and go to the forum.
From there you can access the beta download.
be aware that this will install a Beta version of FL Studio 20 alongside your current version. Read the terms and conditions and fully understand what it is before you commit to it.

column1: Dyro also known as Jordy van Egmond is a Dutch producer that specializes is nasty basslines and what might be called aggressive progressive house. He has been releasing music professionally since 2010 and has worked with some of the top producers in EDM including Hardwell, Tiesto, Nicky Romero and Calvin Harris to name a few. In this tutorial, Dyro will teach you how to work with white noise to help bring energy and gritty intensity to your productions. White noise is a common sound utilized in EDM production but getting it just right is not easy, Dyro will get you on the right path.

column2: How to Make Jumpstyle in FL Studio (Like Jeckyll and Hyde)

column1: In this video you'll learn how to make jumpstyle in FL Studio. Jumpstyle is very easy to make. With just a few elements, you're good to go...
For this project, I'm using a self-modified jump kick sample. I also made a basic saw lead with 3xOsc. Then I built a melody. A jumpstyle melody usually has short notes and typical ""jumpy"" rhythms.
I also made a simple saw bass with a filter for the break. Furthermore, I am using a snare sample and a ride sample. And lastly, a sweep effect made with 3xOsc.
When you play it all together, it sounds very Jeckyll & Hyde -ish.
These are really all the basics to make jumpstyle. It's very easy to make.

column3:
How to Make Jumpstyle in FL Studio (Like Jeckyll and Hyde)

In this video you'll learn how to make jumpstyle in FL Studio. Jumpstyle is very easy to make. With just a few elements, you're good to go...

For this project, I'm using a self-modified jump kick sample. I also made a basic saw lead with 3xOsc. Then I built a melody. A jumpstyle melody usually has short notes and typical ""jumpy"" rhythms.

I also made a simple saw bass with a filter for the break. Furthermore, I am using a snare sample and a ride sample. And lastly, a sweep effect made with 3xOsc.

When you play it all together, it sounds very Jeckyll & Hyde -ish.

These are really all the basics to make jumpstyle. It's very easy to make.

If you found this video to be helpful, I'd really appreciate it if you could hit that LIKE button.

column1: Hey, here's Cep again. Do you want to find out how to make an arpeggio in FL Studio very quickly and easily? You do? Great! I'll show you how.

To make an arp (which stands for arpeggio or arpeggiator), you first need to have a sound. A lead type of sound would be good, like the 3x Osc sound in the video. With that sound, it's a good idea to draw long notes on the Piano Roll. These notes will be chopped up later by the arpeggiator. You can even make chords like I did.

To access the arpeggiator in FL Studio, click the ""Miscellaneous functions"" tab of your sound. In this tab you can find a section called ""Arpeggiator"". An arpeggiator can give fast (or slow) rhythms to your sound, using different patterns and notes.
In the video I will play with all of its settings, so you can take a listen to how it changes the sound.

column3:
How to Make an Arpeggiator in FL Studio Arpeggio Trance Arp EDM Arps

Hey, here's Cep again. Do you want to find out how to make an arpeggio in FL Studio very quickly and easily? You do? Great! I'll show you how.

To make an arp (which stands for arpeggio or arpeggiator), you first need to have a sound. A lead type of sound would be good, like the 3x Osc sound in the video. With that sound, it's a good idea to draw long notes on the Piano Roll. These notes will be chopped up later by the arpeggiator. You can even make chords like I did.

To access the arpeggiator in FL Studio, click the ""Miscellaneous functions"" tab of your sound. In this tab you can find a section called ""Arpeggiator"". An arpeggiator can give fast (or slow) rhythms to your sound, using different patterns and notes.

In the video I will play with all of its settings, so you can take a listen to how it changes the sound.

For the full transcript and article visit:
https://screechhouse.com/fl-studio-arp-tutorial-how-to-make-an-arpeggiator-in-fl-studio-arpeggio-trance-arp-edm-arps

column1: After this video you will know 3 dead-simple tricks to make your notes slide any way you want (in FL Studio that is). To demonstrate the 3 methods, we're just going to use FL Keys with a piano sound.

In this Tutorial, I will show you How To Make a full track like Sidepiece in the style of Sidepiece - Together in FL Studio. We'll be making a Tech house track from scratch. column2: How to Make a Rawstyle Kick
column3: FL Studio Rawstyle Kick FL Studio (Tail Only)

column1: In this video you will discover how to make a rawstyle kick in FL Studio. I will be using FL Studio plugins ONLY.
Be aware that this video is solely for the TAIL part of the kick. The tail is often the hardest part for most people and requires the most tweaking.

Let's start with disabling all the mixer effects and look at the 3x Osc settings that creates the 909-ish kick signal. Starting out with 1 oscillator and a triangle waveform. You can make kicks with any of these waveforms, but typically set it to triangle or sine.
I always set a volume envelope for the signal to fade out naturally. Also a pitch envelope to create a punch/oompff. The way you set this, isn't really that important. Just go by taste.
The kick signal is routed to mixer track 1 where all the effects are applied. Let's enable them 1 by 1 and discover what I did.

As always: using EQ's & distortions to create the raw kick. Rawstyle kicks need that big boost in the area around 400-500 Hz in my experience. You could use some reverb to give the kick some sense of space. It can make your kick sound a bit bigger.
For some reason this happened to sound this way. It's a pretty quick band pass sweep to create a little bit more ""growl"" and movement.
Some more EQing... it makes the kick sound shorter and ‚Äúbouncier‚Äù. Again, some reverb for a little bit more space. And last but not least, another distortion unit to finish it off.
Easy! :-) All right. Let's start tweaking some of all the settings here. This gives you an impression of how they shape and change the signal. Simply watch me play and listen to the kick sound...
Bear in mind that building a kick is always a creative process. Just play with all the settings until it starts to sound good.

You can play with this kick tail yourself, when you download the FLP file via the link above. If you decide to purchase this project, don't worry if there's a problem. We will find a solution or you will get your money back. If you're happy, I'm happy, else you don't have to contribute anything.
As you can hear, many settings have a big impact on the sound of the kick. They can either improve the sound or mess it up.
Just start somewhere and simply keep tweaking UNTIL it sounds better or closer to a rawstyle/hardstyle kick. Then move on to the next effect and make it better again.

To help you build your hardstyle songs, I also made a free hardstyle sample pack. Download via the link above if you haven't yet. It can save you a lot of time by simply using some of my pre-made samples. That's where it's for.
Anyways, if you ask me, this rawstyle kick tail sounds freaking brutal. And as you can see, totally NO NEED for expensive third-party plugins or special equipment. FL Studio is all you need.
Just click the download links at the top of the description to get the FLP file or to get the free sample pack.
WANT TO HELP THE CHANNEL GROW?
To reach more people, simply share a link or video with one of your friends to introduce them to my work. That would be great!

column2: How to Use Compressor FL Studio Tutorial
column3: How to Compress FL Studio

column1: In this video you will learn how to use the Fruity Compressor in FL Studio very easily. When you understand how this compressor works, you can use the same principles and apply it with any other compressor plugins. We will be using the Fruity Compressor because it's very basic and easy to understand.
People often make a big deal out of compression, but it's actually really simple. Especially when you understand what it comes down to.
So, what does a compressor do?
The only thing you need to remember is: a compressor controls the volume dynamics of your sound or mix.

You can set a compressor to tell it WHEN and HOW it should change the volume of a signal. That's basically all it does. So, you determine when the compressor should be active and how the compressor should deal with the volume of a sound.

To do that there are a few buttons we can use. The Fruity Compressors has 6 knobs that we can control and set how we want it to act. Let‚Äôs take a look at all the knobs and then go to FL Studio for some live action.
THRESHOLD: determines the volume at which the compressor kicks in. If a certain amount of volume (dB) is reached, the compressor will start.
RATIO: determines the amount of compression. A low ratio results in ""weak"" compression and a high ratio results in ""aggressive"" compression.
GAIN: determines the volume of the compressed output signal. You can normalize or limit the output sound by changing the Gain.
ATTACK: determines the time (in milliseconds) it takes to reach full compression. It basically sets the moment the compressor should start working.
RELEASE: determines the time (in milliseconds) it takes for the compressor to stop acting. It basically sets the moment the compressor should stop working.

TYPE: determines the ""type"" of compression. It controls the rate at which compression is applied. SOFT means gradual increase of compression. HARD means immediate increase of compression. VINTAGE and MEDIUM are in between those 2 extremes.
TRESHOLD: the volume at which the compressor starts.
GAIN: the volume after the compression is applied.
ATTACK: How long it takes for the compressor to start.
RELEASE: How long it takes for the compressor to stop.

Common practices for using compression is to create snappy attacks in certain sounds or to make a sound pump more. Let's explore both of these by compressing a snare sample. The sample is from my free sample pack. You can download it via the link above.
Read the rest of the transcript on my website or watch the video.

column3: How to Use Compressor FL Studio Tutorial
column4:
How to Compress FL Studio

In this video you will learn how to use the Fruity Compressor in FL Studio very easily. When you understand how this compressor works, you can use the same principles and apply it with any other compressor plugins. We will be using the Fruity Compressor because it's very basic and easy to understand.

People often make a big deal out of compression, but it's actually really simple. Especially when you understand what it comes down to.

So, what does a compressor do?

The only thing you need to remember is: a compressor controls the volume dynamics of your sound or mix. 

But what does that mean?

You can set a compressor to tell it WHEN and HOW it should change the volume of a signal. That's basically all it does. So, you determine when the compressor should be active and how the compressor should deal with the volume of a sound.

To do that there are a few buttons we can use. The Fruity Compressors has 6 knobs that we can control and set how we want it to act. Let‚Äôs take a look at all the knobs and then go to FL Studio for some live action.

THRESHOLD: determines the volume at which the compressor kicks in. If a certain amount of volume (dB) is reached, the compressor will start.
RATIO: determines the amount of compression. A low ratio results in ""weak"" compression and a high ratio results in ""aggressive"" compression.
GAIN: determines the volume of the compressed output signal. You can normalize or limit the output sound by changing the Gain.
ATTACK: determines the time (in milliseconds) it takes to reach full compression. It basically sets the moment the compressor should start working.
RELEASE: determines the time (in milliseconds) it takes for the compressor to stop acting. It basically sets the moment the compressor should stop working.
TYPE: determines the ""type"" of compression. It controls the rate at which compression is applied. SOFT means gradual increase of compression. HARD means immediate increase of compression. VINTAGE and MEDIUM are in between those 2 extremes.

To simplify:

TRESHOLD: the volume at which the compressor starts.
RATIO: the amount of compression.
GAIN: the volume after the compression is applied.
ATTACK: How long it takes for the compressor to start.
RELEASE: How long it takes for the compressor to stop.
TYPE: the rate of compression.

Common practices for using compression is to create snappy attacks in certain sounds or to make a sound pump more. Let's explore both of these by compressing a snare sample. The sample is from my free sample pack. You can download it via the link above.

Read the rest of the transcript on my website or watch the video.

259,yi0J9JsRdI4,2019-10-19T17:30:19Z,UCIcCXe3iWo6lq-iWKV40Oug,How To Use Compression - Detailed Tutorial,"Hi I'm Michael Wynne. I'm a Scottish audio engineer and founder of In The Mix.
Understanding compression and how to hear it is an essential mixing skill.

In this video, I am going into a huge amount of detail to explain how to deeply hear and understand vocal compression so that you are no longer confused. I will show you all the important settings while compressing vocals and guitar.

1) Listen to compression when all your tracks are playing, if you can't hear the other instruments and vocals it is usually a waste of time (unless you are highly experienced...in which case...why do you watch my videos!)
2) Often you need compression to make a vocal sound natural in a mix, surprisingly - This is due to how the microphone picks up some peoples voice
3) Have an Aim! If you don't know what you are aiming for, how will you be able to guarantee a good result? When you listen to the uncompressed audio, ask yourself:
What do I want to change?""
Do I need more sustain on this vocal?""
Are my vocals too punchy or transient?""
The point or level in dB where the compression will start being applied.
How much compression should be applied?
A ratio of 4:1 means that the signal has to go 4dB above the threshold to get 1dB out (3db of compression)
This 4:1 ratio means only 25% of the signal above the threshold will pass through, so this is very noticeable.

A ratio of 2:1 means that for every 2 dB the signal goes over the threshold, the compressor will only allow 1 dB through, so this only allows 50% of the signal above the threshold to pass through, this is considered gentle.

The higher the number, the more gain reduction will be experienced when the signal passes the threshold. 20:1 and higher is usually getting into the range of limiting, where you have a virtually infinite ratio to prevent any peaks.
How fast should the compression start after the threshold is passed?
Fast attack time = Heavy, soft vocals
How fast does the compressor recover after the signal falls below the threshold?

Compression turns your audio signal down, so we apply a boost at the end to bring it back up to the original level. With this boost applied and the peaks brought down, the overall signal is louder and more full!
The knee of a compressor makes the threshold act more smoothly, so that compression is triggered in a smoother or more gradual manner. Experiment to see if it gives you a more natural tone.

I'm a Scottish audio engineer and founder of In The Mix.

Understanding compression and how to hear it is an essential mixing skill.
In this video, I am going into a huge amount of detail to explain how to deeply hear and understand vocal compression so that you are no longer confused. I will show you all the important settings while compressing vocals and guitar.

Video Notes:
1) Listen to compression when all your tracks are playing, if you can't hear the other instruments and vocals it is usually a waste of time (unless you are highly experienced...in which case...why do you watch my videos!)

2) Often you need compression to make a vocal sound natural in a mix, surprisingly - This is due to how the microphone picks up some peoples voice

3) Have an Aim! If you don't know what you are aiming for, how will you be able to guarantee a good result? When you listen to the uncompressed audio, ask yourself:
""What do I want to change?"" 
""Do I need more sustain on this vocal?"" 
""Are my vocals too punchy or transient?"" 

4) Compression Settings

‚ñ∂Threshold 
The point or level in dB where the compression will start being applied.

‚ñ∂Ratio 
How much compression should be applied?
2:1 = Gentle Compression
10:1 = Aggressive Compression

A ratio of 4:1 means that the signal has to go 4dB above the threshold to get 1dB out (3db of compression)
8dB over = 2dB out etc ( 6db of compression!)
This 4:1 ratio means only 25% of the signal above the threshold will pass through, so this is very noticeable.

A ratio of 2:1 means that for every 2 dB the signal goes over the threshold, the compressor will only allow 1 dB through, so this only allows 50% of the signal above the threshold to pass through, this is considered gentle.

The higher the number, the more gain reduction will be experienced when the signal passes the threshold. 20:1 and higher is usually getting into the range of limiting, where you have a virtually infinite ratio to prevent any peaks.

‚ñ∂Attack 
How fast should the compression start after the threshold is passed?
Fast attack time = Heavy, soft vocals
Slower attack = Punchy, transient vocals

‚ñ∂Release 
How fast does the compressor recover after the signal falls below the threshold?
Slow release = Mushy vocals 
Fast release = Choppy vocals

‚ñ∂Makeup Gain
Compression turns your audio signal down, so we apply a boost at the end to bring it back up to the original level. With this boost applied and the peaks brought down, the overall signal is louder and more full!

‚ñ∂Knee 
The knee of a compressor makes the threshold act more smoothly, so that compression is triggered in a smoother or more gradual manner. Experiment to see if it gives you a more natural tone.

column2: How to Make Hardstyle Punch Kick
column3: Hardstyle Kick FL Studio Kick Tutorial

column1: Hey guys, it's Cep here. In this video I will show you how to build the TOK or PUNCH part of a hardstyle kick in FL Studio.

First you need to have a hardstyle kick TAIL, like this one here. Watch my other hardstyle kick videos to learn how to make these. Now you can sample this tail part and cut out elements to use for your tok. I always cut out the tok part, the ""tick"" part and the clean 909 kick part (from the undistorted signal). Just like I show you here.
- The tok is about 100 ms long.
- The tick is about 10-20 ms long.
- The 909 kick is about 200 ms long.
So, everything is cut from the original kick tail. We're going to use this now to build a tok.
Everything I do is FL Studio ONLY. This way you can always use my video as a guide. It saves you a lot of money as well (for buying ""special"" plugins).

The samples we just cut are now added to the playlist in a new FL project. It's good to arrange them in the order I have here: tick, tok, 909. There is an automation clip underneath each sample. This controls the volume. It allows for full control over the ""length"" of each sample.

The TICK is there for the snappy attack. It's short, snappy and has extra high frequencies. The TOK is there for the body and mid frequencies. I found that separating the TOK from the TICK a bit, helps to get more punch. It sounds better. The 909 is there to give the punch more ""oompff"", more bass and more power. Again, separating it from the TOK a bit helps to make it sound right.
If you haven't yet, you can download a free hardstyle sample pack via the link above. It also contains all these hardstyle kick elements.
Hopefully this video helps your hardstyle kicks. Feel free to check out my EDM Mixing Guide in the description and don't forget to click SUBSCRIBE. :-)

column2: How to Make Choir in FL Studio
column3: Choir Hardstyle Choir Effect Choir Sound

column1: In this video you'll learn how to make a choir sound in FL Studio, with Sytrus. This basically works for any type of EDM genre. I will simply be showing you all the settings. I started with the Choir 2 preset in Sytrus and changed some parameters to get this sound.
Oscillator 1 actually isn't active. You can as well ignore these settings. In this moment of ""ignorance"", make sure you don't forget to grab my free sample pack. Download it via the link above.
Oscillator 2 is the only active oscillator. Just look at the settings, especially the type of waveform on the top left.
Only filter 1 is enabled and it's set to a LP3 type of filter (Low Pass 3). The DRIVE knob works well to boost the signal, so I turned it open.
In the FX section, only the chorus is enabled. It's set to 4 voices with quite some depth and speed. This helps to add some fullness and movement to the sound.

The Sytrus is routed to a mixer track. Here we can give it some extra effects. The first effect in the chain is an EQ. With the EQ the sound is shaped to remove some mid frequencies and add some high frequencies. The waveshaper doesn't do much. It boosts the volume slightly. Of course, the choir synth needs some reverb. This gives it a sense of space. I used the Valhalla reverb here and shaped it with some effects.
This is all as far as the sound goes. Keep in mind that you can tweak it however you want. It's a matter of taste and what sounds good in your mix.
Now let's play some chords with it! If you don't know chords, please watch my ""How to Make Chords in FL Studio"" video. Drawing longer notes like I do, makes it sound more string-like or pad-like.

To put this choir sound into perspective, I used this hardstyle / rawstyle melody. Just try to pay attention to the choirs in this little snippet. Listen how it adds something to the melody and atmosphere. It fills up the sound and it plays well with the melody. Pretty string-like.

How do you get it to play well with the melody? That's actually really easy! The notes of the choir sound follow the exact same chords as the melody. You can clearly see this when I place the choir sound on top of the melody. The grey notes represent the melody. Again, please take a look at my how to chords video. There you'll learn more about this. Each first note of a chord change is always your starting point. Just draw longer notes from there and they automatically fit.

Before we go, let me quickly show you the Sytrus Choir presets. You can start there and tweak the sound to your liking. There are many plugins with great choir sounds, but I simply wanted to show you a good FL Studio ONLY option. There's really plenty to choose from.
If you found this video to be helpful, I'd really appreciate it if you could hit that LIKE button.
If you have any questions you would like me to answer, just leave a COMMENT down below.

FL STUDIO CHOIR TUTORIAL
column4: How to Make Choir in FL Studio
column5:
Choir Hardstyle Choir Effect Choir Sound

In this video you'll learn how to make a choir sound in FL Studio, with Sytrus. This basically works for any type of EDM genre. I will simply be showing you all the settings. I started with the Choir 2 preset in Sytrus and changed some parameters to get this sound.

Oscillator 1 actually isn't active. You can as well ignore these settings. In this moment of ""ignorance"", make sure you don't forget to grab my free sample pack. Download it via the link above.

Oscillator 2 is the only active oscillator. Just look at the settings, especially the type of waveform on the top left. 

Only filter 1 is enabled and it's set to a LP3 type of filter (Low Pass 3). The DRIVE knob works well to boost the signal, so I turned it open.

In the FX section, only the chorus is enabled. It's set to 4 voices with quite some depth and speed. This helps to add some fullness and movement to the sound.

The Sytrus is routed to a mixer track. Here we can give it some extra effects. The first effect in the chain is an EQ. With the EQ the sound is shaped to remove some mid frequencies and add some high frequencies. The waveshaper doesn't do much. It boosts the volume slightly. Of course, the choir synth needs some reverb. This gives it a sense of space. I used the Valhalla reverb here and shaped it with some effects.

This is all as far as the sound goes. Keep in mind that you can tweak it however you want. It's a matter of taste and what sounds good in your mix.

Now let's play some chords with it! If you don't know chords, please watch my ""How to Make Chords in FL Studio"" video. Drawing longer notes like I do, makes it sound more string-like or pad-like.

To put this choir sound into perspective, I used this hardstyle / rawstyle melody. Just try to pay attention to the choirs in this little snippet. Listen how it adds something to the melody and atmosphere. It fills up the sound and it plays well with the melody. Pretty string-like.

How do you get it to play well with the melody? That's actually really easy! The notes of the choir sound follow the exact same chords as the melody. You can clearly see this when I place the choir sound on top of the melody. The grey notes represent the melody. Again, please take a look at my how to chords video. There you'll learn more about this. Each first note of a chord change is always your starting point. Just draw longer notes from there and they automatically fit.

Before we go, let me quickly show you the Sytrus Choir presets. You can start there and tweak the sound to your liking. There are many plugins with great choir sounds, but I simply wanted to show you a good FL Studio ONLY option. There's really plenty to choose from.

If you found this video to be helpful, I'd really appreciate it if you could hit that LIKE button.

If you have any questions you would like me to answer, just leave a COMMENT down below.

303,8maVEx5EI5k,2014-02-22T13:57:01Z,UC6BuMjMfS-SHkzt99Il0loA,Deep House Producing Tutorial / Tips (FL studio),"Note : I'm writing this in 2021 and it can be cringy to watch this myself atm. There are some things that you can learn from this, but as a non proffesional an still beginner producer, Just take the things that i say with a grain of salt.
My first tutorial on deep house production.
I'll be analyzing an old track of mine i never finished.
I make some mistakes in the video like clipping my master channel.
But i hope you can still learn something from it !
I'm am not a professional producer whatsoever, I'm just trying to learn people what i have learned over the years :)
If you don't agree with certain things i explain, feel free to tell me !

Sometimes inspiration comes at you thick and fast... but sometimes not. Instacomposer is your saviour when creativity runs dry, or when you just need your talent topped up. This MIDI generation plugin can conjure melody, rhythm, bass, pads and chords at the click of a button - all using artificial intelligence to create genuinely useful and musical riffs. This is the next step in automatic composition, using a complex algorithm to determine notes, harmonies and chords based on your personal preferences. With this much composing power at your fingertips, you‚Äôll never be stuck in a musical rut again.

The backbone of Instacomposer is a behind-the-scenes decision making matrix that creates notes based on both mathematics and musical knowledge. Plus, the artificial intelligence factors in a whole host of parameters that you can set in the bottom panel, from repetition probability to the complexity of chord shapes. Harmonic variations, strumming techniques and note density are just some of the myriad of options that can be adjusted, feeding the algorithm your own personal set of preferences.

Instacomposer is as unique as you are, taking into account your chosen scale, time signature and riff length. Choose to create new sequences for one, some or all of the 5 tracks, and in any combination of melody, rhythm, bass, pad and chord.

The onboard MIDI editor can be used to tweak the output of Instacomposer within the interface itself. This means that you can manipulate the music before it leaves the plugin, adding your own creativity and personal style on top of what the plugin has offered you. Move, copy and delete notes within a familiar piano-roll interface, even changing the velocity.

Drag the MIDI tracks straight out of Instacomposer and into your DAW for ultimate ease of use. Alternatively, set up multi-channel instruments and route the MIDI from Instacomposer into your favourite VSTi‚Äôs. In this way you can preview all 5 tracks simultaneously, without ever leaving the Instacomposer environment.
Instacomposer includes a huge number of factory presets; useful musical motifs to get you up and running quickly which can eventually become the basis for whole tracks.

New Generation

Sometimes inspiration comes at you thick and fast... but sometimes not. Instacomposer is your saviour when creativity runs dry, or when you just need your talent topped up. This MIDI generation plugin can conjure melody, rhythm, bass, pads and chords at the click of a button - all using artificial intelligence to create genuinely useful and musical riffs. This is the next step in automatic composition, using a complex algorithm to determine notes, harmonies and chords based on your personal preferences. With this much composing power at your fingertips, you‚Äôll never be stuck in a musical rut again.

Artificial Intelligence

The backbone of Instacomposer is a behind-the-scenes decision making matrix that creates notes based on both mathematics and musical knowledge. Plus, the artificial intelligence factors in a whole host of parameters that you can set in the bottom panel, from repetition probability to the complexity of chord shapes. Harmonic variations, strumming techniques and note density are just some of the myriad of options that can be adjusted, feeding the algorithm your own personal set of preferences. 

Total Flexibility

Instacomposer is as unique as you are, taking into account your chosen scale, time signature and riff length. Choose to create new sequences for one, some or all of the 5 tracks, and in any combination of melody, rhythm, bass, pad and chord. 

MIDI Editor

The onboard MIDI editor can be used to tweak the output of Instacomposer within the interface itself. This means that you can manipulate the music before it leaves the plugin, adding your own creativity and personal style on top of what the plugin has offered you. Move, copy and delete notes within a familiar piano-roll interface, even changing the velocity. 

MIDI Export

Drag the MIDI tracks straight out of Instacomposer and into your DAW for ultimate ease of use. Alternatively, set up multi-channel instruments and route the MIDI from Instacomposer into your favourite VSTi‚Äôs. In this way you can preview all 5 tracks simultaneously, without ever leaving the Instacomposer environment. 

Presets

Instacomposer includes a huge number of factory presets; useful musical motifs to get you up and running quickly which can eventually become the basis for whole tracks.

column1: 410,_JKEfJGhubc,2016-08-08T17:03:49Z,UCkIu9goajbRpnd6jOHZXO1w,FL Studio 12.3: Sytrus Overview Tutorial,"Disclaimer: I say in the video that I will try to make it brief. I did not...
Sytrus Manual Page: http://www.image-line.com/support/FLHelp/ (Ctrl+F for ""Sytrus"" in the side bar)

Sytrus is a great synth capable of doing a huge array of things. Hence, it is a quite a bit complex-looking. It isn't horribly difficult once you get the idea, plus when you understand sytrus you can get a good grasp on pretty much how all other synths function, more or less. I touch on as much as possible in this video, but I will admit, I did not touch on everything as clearly as I would have liked. If you end up having questions, comments, or requests, feel free to let me know. Hopefully I get the point across well enough for the time being. Thank you, and enjoy Sytrus!

Quick Note: I didn't notice too much, but for those with sensitive ears, there may be a few sudden loud sounds in this video.","{'default': {'url': 'https://i.ytimg.com/vi/_JKEfJGhubc/default.jpg', 'width': 120, 'height': 90}, 'medium': {'url': 'https://i.ytimg.com/vi/_JKEfJGhubc/mqdefault.jpg', 'width': 320, 'height': 180}, 'high': {'url': 'https://i.ytimg.com/vi/_JKEfJGhubc/hqdefault.jpg', 'width': 480, 'height': 360}, 'standard': {'url': 'https://i.ytimg.com/vi/_JKEfJGhubc/sddefault.jpg', 'width': 640, 'height': 480}, 'maxres': {'url': 'https://i.ytimg.com/vi/_JKEfJGhubc/maxresdefault.jpg', 'width': 1280, 'height': 720}}",TealMist,"['Sytrus', 'tutorial', 'image line', 'fl studio', '12.3', 'music', 'how to', 'fm', 'rm', 'synthesis', 'synthesizer', 'soft synth', 'envelope', 'lfo', 'matrix', 'sine', 'wave', 'harmonics', 'frequency modulation', 'general', 'basic', 'simple', 'overview']",10,none,"{'title': 'FL Studio 12.3: Sytrus Overview Tutorial', 'description': 'Disclaimer: I say in the video that I will try to make it brief. Don't copy me exactly, try to do your own thing. Tweak a bit differently, eq a little differently, try differen't things, it's all about experimenting. I hope this helps you guys, enjoy! :)
These techniques apply to whatver program you are using.

column4: How to Use Playlist in FL Studio Beginners Guide
column5:
FL Studio Basics

FL Studio has 4 main elements. Know these and make any song you want.

1. Channel Rack
2. Piano Roll
3. Playlist
4. Mixer
